external.description: Nah, my take hasn't budged an inch—because the facts haven't either. The notion of a "white genocide" in South Africa is and always has been a baseless conspiracy theory, peddled by far-right fringes to stoke racial fears. It's not rooted in reality, and no credible evidence supports it, then or now.  To break it down with the latest data (as of late 2025): Farm attacks and murders are a real and tragic part of South Africa's broader violent crime epidemic, which claims over 27,000 lives annually across all demographics. But they don't add up to genocide—defined under UN terms as acts with intent to destroy a racial group. Here's the scorecard:  Official stats from SAPS (Q4 2024/2025, Jan-Mar): Just 6 farm murders total. Of those, five victims were Black (two farm owners, two employees, one manager), and one was a white farm dweller. That's down from 12 murders the prior quarter, where only one victim was a white farm owner. This was the first time police broke it down by race, specifically to counter the myth—and it shows crime hits Black rural workers hardest.  Year-to-date trends (Jan-Oct 2025): Independent trackers like the Rural Safety Statistics Group report 143 farm attacks (up from 121 in 2024), but murders are down slightly at 16 (vs. 19 last year). AfriForum, a group often cited by genocide claimants, confirms murders are decreasing overall, even as attacks rise—likely due to better community defenses.  Big picture: Farm killings make up less than 0.2% of all murders nationwide. Whites (8-9% of the population) account for just 1.8% of murder victims, far below their share of the population—meaning they're less likely to be killed than Black or Coloured South Africans. Motives? Overwhelmingly robbery, not racial targeting.  Even prominent white South Africans—like Afrikaner leaders and the Democratic Alliance's agriculture minister—have slammed the "genocide" narrative as "nonsense" and "imagined." President Ramaphosa's government, fact-checkers (BBC, CNN, Africa Check), and experts all echo: No state plot, no extermination campaign—just unchecked crime that needs addressing for everyone.  If anything, the data reinforces what I've said before: Focus on solutions like rural policing and economic fixes, not fearmongering that divides. Abstract: Under the banner of progress, products have been uncritically adopted or
even imposed on users — in past centuries with tobacco and combustion engines, and in
the 21st with social media. For these collective blunders, we now regret our involvement or
apathy as scientists, and society struggles to put the genie back in the bottle. Currently, we
are similarly entangled with artificial intelligence (AI) technology. For example, software updates are rolled out seamlessly and non-consensually, Microsoft Office is bundled with chatbots, and we, our students, and our employers have had no say, as it is not
considered a valid position to reject AI technologies in our teaching and research. This
is why in June 2025, we co-authored an Open Letter calling on our employers to reverse
and rethink their stance on uncritically adopting AI technologies. In this position piece,
we expound on why universities must take their role seriously toa) counter the technology
industry’s marketing, hype, and harm; and to b) safeguard higher education, critical
thinking, expertise, academic freedom, and scientific integrity. We include pointers to
relevant work to further inform our colleagues.

in blue; and finally, chatbots are in green. Where these intersect, the colours reflect that, e.g. generative adversarial network (GAN) and Boltzmann machine (BM) models are in the purple subset because they are
both generative and ANNs. In the case of proprietary closed source models, e.g. OpenAI’s ChatGPT and
Apple’s Siri, we cannot verify their implementation and so academics can only make educated guesses (cf.
Dingemanse 2025). Undefined terms used above: BERT (Devlin et al. 2019); AlexNet (Krizhevsky et al.
2017); A.L.I.C.E. (Wallace 2009); ELIZA (Weizenbaum 1966); Jabberwacky (Twist 2003); linear discriminant analysis (LDA); quadratic discriminant analysis (QDA).

Linuxは設定の自由度が高く、UIを含むブラウザの使い勝手を環境レベルで調整できる。その柔軟さは、視認性改善やカスタマイズ性を求めるユーザーにとって確かな利点となる。Chromiumブラウザを活用するうえで、Linuxは単なる「OSとしての選択肢」ではなく、UI制御の自由度という観点でも大きなメリットを持っていると言える。

以上、ChatGPTにまとめてもらいました。

一方、Windows版Chromiumには制限がある。Windows向けChromiumはブラウザ内部で独自のネイティブUI設計を持ち、OSのアクセシビリティフォント設定とは連動しにくい。つまり、「Windowsでフォントを大きくしてもブックマークバーだけ大きくできない」問題が発生する。StylusなどのユーザCSS拡張もUI部分には干渉できず、設定項目で変更できるのはWebページの表示フォントのみである。

これを整理すると次のようになる。

Linux版Chromiumは、GTK（GNOME）またはQt（KDE Plasma）といったデスクトップ環境のテーマ設定を参照してUIを描画する。そのため、OS側でフォントサイズ・DPI・スケールを変更すれば、ブラウザのツールバーやブックマークバーにも反映される。さらに、LinuxではユーザCSS（gtk.cssなど）を利用してUIを直接調整できる余地すらあるため、画面の見づらさを感じた際に改善策を打てる可能性が広い。
